            <div class="section">
                <div class="section-title">Decision Framework for Ownership</div>
                
                <div class="methodology-box">
                    <h3 style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Note on Food Cost:</h3>
                    Current 33.2% food cost is factored into all scenarios. This should naturally improve to 30-31% as sales volume increases and operational efficiency improves. Scenarios below focus primarily on labor right-sizing, which is the immediate controllable factor.
                </div>
                
                <div class="methodology-box" style="margin-top: 1rem;">
                    <h3 style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Option A: Conservative Approach</h3>
                    <strong>Month 1-2:</strong> Implement Scenario 2 (Right-Sized, 48% labor)<br>
                    <strong>Month 3-6:</strong> Execute growth plan to reach Scenario 3<br>
                    <strong>Pros:</strong> Less staff disruption, maintains service quality while fixing fundamentals<br>
                    <strong>Cons:</strong> Loses $11K/month for 2 months = $22K additional loss<br>
                    <strong>Total 6-month P&L:</strong> -$22K (months 1-2) + break-even (months 3-4) + modest profit (months 5-6) = <strong>-$15K net</strong>
                </div>
                
                <div class="methodology-box" style="margin-top: 1rem;">
                    <h3 style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Option B: Aggressive Approach</h3>
                    <strong>Month 1:</strong> Implement Scenario 1 (Survival, 43% labor) immediately<br>
                    <strong>Month 2-6:</strong> Execute growth plan while maintaining lean operations<br>
                    <strong>Pros:</strong> Stops bleeding fastest, forces discipline<br>
                    <strong>Cons:</strong> Extreme burnout risk, quality suffers during transition<br>
                    <strong>Total 6-month P&L:</strong> -$16K (month 1) + gradual improvement = <strong>-$8K net</strong> if growth succeeds
                </div>
                
                <div class="methodology-box" style="margin-top: 1rem; background: var(--success-soft); border-color: var(--success);">
                    <h3 style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Recommended: Hybrid Approach</h3>
                    <strong>Week 1-2:</strong> Cut to 13-14 staff (between Scenarios 1 & 2)<br>
                    <strong>Month 1-3:</strong> Operate at 45% labor while launching marketing<br>
                    <strong>Month 3-6:</strong> Execute sales growth + optimize to 35% labor<br>
                    <strong>Pros:</strong> Addresses labor immediately while building revenue, sustainable execution<br>
                    <strong>Cons:</strong> Requires focus and discipline on multiple fronts<br>
                    <strong>Total 6-month P&L:</strong> -$9K (month 1) + -$4K (month 2) + break-even (month 3-4) + modest growth (5-6) = <strong>-$10K net</strong>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="section">
                <div class="section-title">Key Decisions Required This Week</div>
                
                <div class="key-insight">
                    <strong>1. Staff Reductions:</strong> Who stays, who goes? Must happen immediately regardless of scenario chosen. Core team (GM, Oscar, Mikey) + security are locked in. Need to cut from 18 to 10-13 employees.
                </div>
                
                <div class="key-insight">
                    <strong>2. Food Cost Monitoring:</strong> Current 33.2% is expected for first full month without economies of scale. As sales increase, Mikey should track this monthly and implement portion standards to target 30-31% as volume grows. Not an emergency, but worth tracking as part of operational maturity.
                </div>
                
                <div class="key-insight">
                    <strong>3. Marketing Budget:</strong> Commit $2,000-2,500/month for 3-6 months to drive growth. Without sales growth, even with fixed labor costs, the restaurant remains marginally profitable at best.
                </div>
                
                <div class="key-insight">
                    <strong>4. Hours Decision:</strong> Keep current hours (11am-2am/4am) or cut back? Late-night is 25%+ of revenue but requires security costs. This decision affects staffing models significantly.
                </div>
                
                <div class="key-insight">
                    <strong>5. Timeline & Cash Runway:</strong> How many months of losses can the business sustain? If 6+ months â†’ take measured approach. If 2-3 months â†’ emergency survival mode required immediately.
                </div>
                
                <div class="key-insight">
                    <strong>6. Management Structure:</strong> Can Andrew continue as salaried GM ($4,167/month) or transition to hourly? At current sales levels, this represents 6.6% of revenue for one person. Consider whether this is sustainable or if GM role needs restructuring.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <script>
        function switchTab(tabName) {
            // Hide all tab contents
            document.querySelectorAll('.tab-content').forEach(tab => {
                tab.classList.remove('active');
            });
            
            // Remove active class from all nav tabs
            document.querySelectorAll('.nav-tab').forEach(tab => {
                tab.classList.remove('active');
            });
            
            // Show selected tab content
            document.getElementById(tabName).classList.add('active');
            
            // Add active class to clicked nav tab
            event.target.classList.add('active');
            
            // Scroll to top
            window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: 'smooth' });
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
